Que 1: Name any five plots that we can plot using the Seaborn library. Also, state the uses of each plot.
Ans. Scatter Plot (sns.scatterplot)
- Use: Displays the relationship between two continuous variables.
- Example: Plotting sepal length vs. sepal width in the Iris dataset helps identify clusters or correlations.
- Insight: Useful for detecting trends, clusters, and outliers in data.

 2. Line Plot (sns.lineplot)
- Use: Shows trends over time or ordered categories.
- Example: Visualizing monthly sales data to see growth or decline.
- Insight: Ideal for time-series analysis and understanding progression of values.

 3. Histogram / Distribution Plot (sns.histplot / sns.displot)
- Use: Represents the distribution of a single variable.
- Example: Plotting the distribution of customer ages in a dataset.
- Insight: Helps identify skewness, spread, and whether data follows a normal distribution.

 4. Box Plot (sns.boxplot)
- Use: Summarizes data distribution using quartiles and highlights outliers.
- Example: Comparing salary distributions across different departments.
- Insight: Great for spotting variability, median values, and extreme outliers.

5. Heatmap (sns.heatmap)
- Use: Visualizes data in a matrix form with color encoding.
- Example: Correlation matrix of features in a dataset.
- Insight: Useful for identifying relationships, patterns, and high/low values across categories.


Que 2: Load the "fmri" dataset using the load_dataset function of seaborn. Plot a line plot using x =
"timepoint" and y = "signal" for different events and regions.
Note: timepoint, signal, event, and region are columns in the fmri dataset.
Ans. fmri = sns.load_dataset('fmri')
print(fmri.head())

sns.lineplot(x = 'timepoint', y = 'signal', data = fmri)
plt.show()

sns.lineplot(x = 'timepoint', y = 'signal', data = fmri, style= 'region' )
plt.show()

sns.lineplot(x = 'timepoint', y = 'signal', data = fmri, style= 'region',hue = 'event' )
plt.show()

Que 3: Load the "titanic" dataset using the load_dataset function of seaborn. Plot two box plots using x =
'pclass', y = 'age' and y = 'fare'.
Note: pclass, age, and fare are columns in the titanic dataset.
Ans. titanic = sns.load_dataset('titanic')
print(titanic.head())

fig , axes = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(12,6))
sns.boxplot(data = titanic, x='pclass',y='age', ax=axes[0])
axes[0].set_title('ABx')
# plt.show()

sns.boxplot(x='pclass',y='fare', data = titanic, ax= axes[1])
axes[1].set_title('abcd')
plt.show()

Que 4: Use the "diamonds" dataset from seaborn to plot a histogram for the 'price' column. Use the hue
parameter for the 'cut' column of the diamonds dataset.
ANs.diamonds = sns.load_dataset('diamonds')
print(diamonds.head())
sns.histplot(data=diamonds, x= 'price')
plt.show()

 
sns.histplot(data=diamonds,x="price",     hue="cut") 
plt.show() 

Que 5: Use the "iris" dataset from seaborn to plot a pair plot. Use the hue parameter for the "species" column
of the iris dataset.
ANs.iris = sns.load_dataset("iris")

print(iris.head())
sns.pairplot(data = iris , hue='species')
plt.show()

Que 6: Use the "flights" dataset from seaborn to plot a heatmap.
ANs. 
flights = sns.load_dataset("flights")

# Pivot the dataset properly
flights_pivot = flights.pivot(index="month", columns="year", values="passengers")

# Plot heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(flights_pivot, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="YlGnBu")
plt.title("Monthly Passenger Numbers (Flights Dataset)")
plt.show()
